<subSubSection id="389C7AC2B9E628FD488588D14181E8BB" pageId="33" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="48AD47F849E19E2322EFC3EFF176E211" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FC95BBA306B2CC425A7CD755EA5B9BFA" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">Amphi-Beringia</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E0ED6A20229036132B5A6603BF8DBC4E" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="D0DF1FCD5F95FA29B220533AFC8A69C5" bold="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">Comments</emphasis>
: Collected on Bathurst Island by S. Edlund in 1975, this is only the second collection of this species from the CAA, and the first record from Nunavut. 
<normalizedToken id="368A8B7D1A8DCA9FF8D27AAD5B587694" originalValue="Edlund’s">Edlund's</normalizedToken>
collection was shelved in the backlog of the National Herbarium of Canada for nearly 40 years, and was only recently uncovered. However, its significance as a new record was noted on the newsprint accompanying the specimen, indicating its importance was apparent to the collector.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="90191E83A1ACB0BE99EF32ACBD0B8690" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">
Though long known from the alpine tundra of northern Yukon and Alaska (
<bibRefCitation id="CE257A7864BF6D4671C8F028AE1EC779" author="Cody, WJ" journalOrPublisher="NRC Research Press, Ottawa" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" pagination="1 - 669" refId="B22" refString="Cody, WJ, 2000. Flora of the Yukon Territory. NRC Research Press, Ottawa: 1 - 669" title="Flora of the Yukon Territory" year="2000">Cody 2000</bibRefCitation>
), the 1968 collection on Prince Patrick Island (mapped in 
<bibRefCitation id="7AD12961131BFC9419E5640BF24533FE" author="Porsild, AE" journalOrPublisher="National Museum of Natural Sciences, National Museums of Canada, Ottawa" pageId="40" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 667" refId="B76" refString="Porsild, AE, Cody, WJ, 1980. Vascular Plants of the Continental Northwest Territories, Canada. National Museum of Natural Sciences, National Museums of Canada, Ottawa: 1 - 667" title="Vascular Plants of the Continental Northwest Territories, Canada" year="1980">Porsild and Cody 1980</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="D79B25C6F646F9BD421F0D39C50AF126" author="Aiken, SG" journalOrPublisher="NRC Research Press, National Research Council of Canada, Ottawa" pageId="35" pageNumber="58" publicationUrl="http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" refId="B1" refString="Aiken, SG, Dallwitz, MJ, Consaul, LL, McJannet, CL, Boles, RL, Argus, GW, Gillett, JM, Scott, PJ, Elven, R, LeBlanc, MC, Gillespie, LJ, Brysting, AK, Solstad, H, Harris, JG, 2007. Flora of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago: Descriptions, Illustrations, Identification, and Information Retrieval [CD-ROM]. NRC Research Press, National Research Council of Canada, Ottawa, http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" title="Flora of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago: Descriptions, Illustrations, Identification, and Information Retrieval [CD-ROM]" url="http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" year="2007">Aiken et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
)-the first record for the Arctic Islands-extended the range of this species northeastwards by over 1000 km. The second collection on Bathurst Island pushes this species a further 500 km east in the CAA. The apparent gaps in this species distribution may be explained by its habit: when not in flower, it can resemble either the very common 
<taxonomicName id="A93054F78DFE7973B13890683A8F6E78" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="Saxifraga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saxifraga oppositifolia" order="Saxifragales" pageId="33" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oppositifolia">
<emphasis id="7E497FF5C2D4BD0342BDD47A24A2F612" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="56">Saxifraga oppositifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. or a lichen (
<bibRefCitation id="D5D88D09A6AFE3BEB39B303F2F60EC9A" author="Aiken, SG" journalOrPublisher="NRC Research Press, National Research Council of Canada, Ottawa" pageId="35" pageNumber="58" publicationUrl="http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" refId="B1" refString="Aiken, SG, Dallwitz, MJ, Consaul, LL, McJannet, CL, Boles, RL, Argus, GW, Gillett, JM, Scott, PJ, Elven, R, LeBlanc, MC, Gillespie, LJ, Brysting, AK, Solstad, H, Harris, JG, 2007. Flora of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago: Descriptions, Illustrations, Identification, and Information Retrieval [CD-ROM]. NRC Research Press, National Research Council of Canada, Ottawa, http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" title="Flora of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago: Descriptions, Illustrations, Identification, and Information Retrieval [CD-ROM]" url="http://nature.ca/en/research-collections/research-projects/flora-canadian-arctic-archipelago/" year="2007">Aiken et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
); either scenario could account for the paucity of collections from the CAA.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
